<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-163-454  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 163 454.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Decisions  March 1989 v21 n3 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DBMSs need office skills. (Perspective - database decisions) (database management systems) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>White, Colin J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The use of DBMS applications to provide information critical to acompany's success is increasing.andP;  Users who require suchinformation are typically business professionals making extensiveuse of office automation tools such as word processors,information retrieval systems and electronic-mail.andP;  Since thedatabase information and the office systems information arefrequently the same, combining the two seems an obvious next step.andO;The problem, however, is that most office automation tools handleinformation as text, while most DBMSs employ a record-orientedapproach.andP;  Vendors are beginning to provide support for textstorage, but efficient document retrieval and searching remainsproblematic.andP;  Several possible solutions to the problem ofdocument retrieval and searching are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data base management systemsInformation Storage and RetrievalOffice AutomationIntegrated Office Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>